photo.description: Guests may visit the Cologne Cathedral daily at no cost. However, there is a charge to go up into the south tower which has a viewing platform at a height of 97 meters (318ft). Make sure you're ready for a climb of 509 steps as there is no elevator in the tower. including the 24 tons heavy Petersglocke (St. Peter's Bell), cast in 1923.
photo.title: Köln (Cologne) Cathedral, Kölner Dom

photo.description: Nikon and Fuji are the last things you expect to see when you visit Köln (Cologne) for its historic cathedral. Yet, these camera stores are the first things that greet you as you walk towards the cathedral entrance, as these shops are set against one of the cathedral walls. You can see the Köln (Cologne) cathedral itself towering behind the commercial establishments. The Köln cathedral is almost adjoining the Hauptbahnhof, it's just a few minutes walk. It was freezing cold and was beginning to rain. (Jan. 2008)
photo.title: Köln (Cologne) Cathedral, Kölner Dom

photo.description: Cologne's magnificent Cathedral is the most renowned landmark in the city and serves as the seat of the Archbishop of Cologne. It is one of the largest churches in the world and for some time the cathedral even held the title of the world's tallest building. (Jan. 2008)

photo.description: At the east end of the Köln cathedral stands its greatest treasure, the Shrine of the Kings. It's a wooden casket containing the relics of the Magi,and is encased in a golden case, studded with jewels. Work on the Shrine of Kings casket was started in 1180, ad it took almost fifty years to complete. (Jan. 2008)

photo.description: Also noteworthy at the Köln cathedral are the large stained glass windows, which cover an area of about 10,000 sq meters (110,000 sq feet) and allow plenty of natural light to enter the building. photo.description: That's a self timer shot of moi inside the Köln cathedral. Totally pooped, and with shaky, wobbly legs after the steep 509 step climb up, in freaking cold weather, I simply had to rest. It's a large cathedral, and there is plenty of seating for the devout. Now I'm not a Christian, in fact I'm not even a believer in God, but sitting in that cathedral for about half an hour with eyes closed and shut off to the world did overwhelm me with a sense of peace and calm. (Jan. 2008)

photo.description: <b>Cologne Cathedral (<i>Kölner Dom<i>) from the <i>Bahnofsvorplatz<i> close to Cologne Central Station (<i>Köln Hauptbahnhof<i>), Germany.<b> Taken on the outward journey for our holiday in Germany (July 2011): London - Köln - Wernigerode (Harz Mountains) - Weimar (Thuringia) - London Official name of the Cathedral is <i>Hohe Domkirche St. Peter und Maria<i> (High Cathedral of Sts. Peter and Mary). It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Construction began in 1248 but was halted in 1473, leaving it unfinished. Work recommenced in the 19th century and was completed, to the original plan, in 1880. The architectural style is Gothic. Photo shows the N side of the cathedral. Scaffolding is for renovations (apparently renovations are almost continuous). The cathedral is a huge landmark which can be seen from considerable distances. Being just across the square (<i>Bahnhofsvorplatz<i>) from the equally impressive <a href"http:flic.krpd9WWkV" rel"nofollow">Cologne Central Station (<i>Köln Hauptbahnhof<i>) <a>, and close to the huge steel Hohenzollern Bridge (<i>Hohenzollernbrücke<i>), this makes for a striking <a href"http:bit.lyTNrpU9" rel"nofollow">contrast<a> in styles, function and history of three huge structures. photo.description: These people spell each other off at certain intervals. A while back I saw a CSI episode involving a dead living statue who had been propped up until he got a bit ripe. photo.description: <b>Cologne Cathedral (<i>Kölner Dom<i>) from one of the platforms of Cologne Central Station (<i>Köln Hauptbahnhof<i>) looking across <i>Bahnofsvorplatz<i> (Germany).<b> Taken on a very overcast day on a work visit to Bonn (November 2007) whilst changing trains. Official name of the Cathedral is <i>Hohe Domkirche St. Peter und Maria<i> (High Cathedral of Sts. Peter and Mary). It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Construction began in 1248 but was halted in 1473, leaving it unfinished. Work recommenced in the 19th century and was completed, to the original plan, in 1880. The architectural style is Gothic. The cathedral is a huge landmark which can be seen from considerable distances. Being just across the square (<i>Bahnhofsvorplatz<i>) from the equally impressive <a href"http:flic.krpd9WWkV" rel"nofollow">Cologne Central Station (<i>Köln Hauptbahnhof<i>) <a>, and close to the huge steel Hohenzollern Bridge (<i>Hohenzollernbrücke<i>), this makes for a striking <a href"http:bit.lyTNrpU9" rel"nofollow">contrast<a> in styles, function and history of three huge structures. This view, taken from one of the station platforms across the eastern corner of <i>Bahnhofsvorplatz<i>, shows how close the station is to the N side of the Cathedral. <a href"http:flic.krpd9WWkV" rel"nofollow">Here<a> is the reverse view taken four years later from near where the white vans are parked in front of the Cathedral here. photo.description: <b>On the steps of Cologne Cathedral (<i>Kölner Dom<i>)<b>. Taken on our return rail journey at the end of our holiday. Today we left Bonn on a local train, and changed at Cologne (<i>Köln<i>) where we had a little bit of spare time. We then took an ICE train to Brussels (Bruxelles Midi), Belgium, where we changed to a Eurostar train for St.Pancras International, London. By coincidence, this gave me the chance to photograph (and contrast) the great arched canopies of different ages, of three famous railway stations all in one day - Cologne Central, Liège Guillemins and London St.Pancras. By another coincidence, we found we were due to cross paths at St.Pancras with some of the family on an outward trip to France. We had some time to spare between changing trains at Cologne (<i>Köln<i>) so we sat in the sun, using the Cathedral steps for our waiting room. <b>Photo<b> by Brian (upper), Jill (lower). © Darkroom Daze <a href"http:bit.ly47tbGf" rel"nofollow">Creative Commons<a>. photo.description: <b><i>Köln Hauptbahnhof<i> (Cologne Central Station, Germany) - one of Europe's great railway stations.<b> Selected shot from our return rail journey at the end of our holiday. Today we left Bonn on a local train, and changed at Cologne (<i>Köln<i>) where we had a little bit of spare time. We then took an ICE train to Brussels (Bruxelles Midi), Belgium, where we changed to a Eurostar train for St.Pancras International, London. By coincidence, this gave me the chance to photograph (and contrast) the great arched canopies of different ages, of three famous railway stations all in one day - Cologne Central, Liège Guillemins and London St.Pancras. By another coincidence, we found we were due to cross paths at St.Pancras with some of the family on an outward trip to France. This station is an important rail hub for Germany and for this part of Europe. The main arched canopy is out of sight away to the L. This smaller canopy is relatively modern, built to cover platform extensions. In the distance is the massive <i>Hohenzollernbrücke<i> (Hohenzollern Bridge), which carries the main railway lines over the River Rhine. Remarkably, this station and bridge are adjacent to the huge medieval cathedral of Cologne (out of sight here, behind us) and make a striking contrast of styles, function and history. This view was taken from near the top of the cathedral steps, looking E at the SE end of the station. In the foreground is a high speed ICE train of Deutsche Bahn (German Railways) and the red train further away, partly on the bridge, is a local train. THE BRIDGE The <i>Hohenzollernbrücke<i> (Hohenzollern Bridge) was constructed between 1907 and 1911 after the old bridge, the <i>Dombrücke<i> (Cathedral Bridge) was demolished. It consists of multiple bow-string cantilevers. This was one of the most important bridges in Germany during World War II but German military engineers blew up the bridge when Allied troops began their assault on Cologne. Three years later, the Hohenzollern Bridge was accessible to pedestrians again and full usage was restored by 1959. Today, more than 1200 trains a day use the Hohenzollern Bridge - the highest usage of any rail bridge in Germany. Source: <a href"http:en.wikipedia.orgwikiHohenzollern_Bridge" rel"nofollow">en.wikipedia.orgwikiHohenzollern_Bridge<a> THE TRAINS The nearer train is a high speed train of the German railway system, <i>Deutsche Bahn<i>. According to the <a href"http:www.eurail.complanningtrains-and-ferrieshigh-speed-trainsice" rel"nofollow">Eurail website<a>, &quot;With a maximum speed of 300 kmh (186 mph) these high-speed trains connect major German cities at hourly intervals. International ICE trains connect Germany with Austria (Wien, Innsbruck), Belgium (Brussels, Liège), Denmark (Copenhagen, Arhus), France (Paris), the Netherlands (Arnhem, Utrecht, Amsterdam) and Switzerland (Zürich, Interlaken).&quot; Although the trains are a German service and brand, ICE stands for 'Inter-City Express' in English. The red train in the distance belongs to the Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn (<i>S-Bahn Rhein-Ruhr<i>), a local and regional rail network covering the Rhine-Ruhr Metropolitan Region. <b>Photo<b> Brian © Darkroom Daze <a href"http:bit.ly47tbGf" rel"nofollow">Creative Commons<a>. If you would like to use or refer to this image, please link or attribute. ID: DSC_5233 - Version 2
